text: To everyone whining about the 'Weight' of the new Jaegers, I think you need to watch the trailers more closely. The main Jaegers are much smaller than the¬†ones from the first movie, or so it appears, as well as Uprising taking place 10 years after the first movie, meaning the Jaegers will be much faster and the movement much more refined, as the PPDC has obviously been spending a lot of time and money making these new Jaegers. And besides, there aren't as many moving parts to the jaegers, because, again, they've been refined and upgraded. And it you watch the final scene in the trailer where the Jaegers are charging at the mega-kaiju, you can see they're running in what would be slow-motion for a human. These Jaegers are still 10,000-ton hunks of metal, they've just been refined. You can still feel the weight behind every movement. Now, If we saw Jaegers sprinting like Usain Bolt and landing punches as quick as a professional boxer, I would be kinda cross, but I personally enjoy the designs of the new fleet. But, then again, if you don't like how they look, then okay, it's your opinion. This is just my 2 cents.

text: Glad I'm not the only one disappointed with this trailer. It's far too different from the first film, my biggest complaint is that it feels cartoonish. The original had a more "realistic" take on the mecha genre and GDT did an amazing job, I'm not getting the same vibes here. The visuals and tone are completely off, it doesn't help that most of the fights seem to take place in the day when the dark environments in the first film added to the visuals. Plus the Jaegers themselves look super slim and are far more active than even Striker Eureka was, I liked the weight the Jaegers had but that seems to be gone now. I don't know if they felt they needed to drastically change the sequel because it didn't do very well financially but I'm let down so far.

text: I've got a theory about the plot of this upcoming movie:  The main antagonists of the movie, the one that the heroes have a personal grudge against, are a group of tiny Kaiju-style parasites who infest human bodies, 'Drift' with the memories of their hapless hosts and act as spies and saboteurs for their masters.  This is my thought process, more or less:  --The narrative weakness of the Precursors, the aliens who made the Kaiju, is that they were rather vague and distant as villains: the heroes and the audience couldn't emotionally interact with them due to their alien nature, their residence in another dimension, and their brief appearance in the climax of Pacific Rim 1.¬† ‚ÄìPacific Rim 2 needs a villainous 'face' of some kind, a relatable antagonist that people can understand, get mad at, and even grudgingly respect. A body-snatcher who can pass as human fits that goal while still being terrifyingly alien. Done well, they can even be complex antagonists, sympathetic towards humans due to the memories they've absorbed, while still determined to fight for the survival of their own 'species'. ‚ÄìIt's also a wicked ironic reversal of the plot's premise: humans pilot giant robots to fight Kaiju, while Kaiju pilot humans to fight Jaegers. ‚ÄìThere's two interesting clips in this trailer that may support this theory: there's that brief snippet where a four star general lets out a face-distorting scream like the imposters from the 1970s 'Invasion of the Body Snatchers'. There's also the scene we see where Jaegers are fighting Jaegers: they may have discovered one of the Kaiju spies and are fighting to keep them from escaping with cutting-edge tech.  This theory might be right, or it might be wrong: what do you guys think?

text: I am seriously worried about this movie.  I looks a little like they Michael Bay'd it.  This is the biggest problem with action or sci fi movies this day and age.  The execs go the previous movie was well liked, how do we do the sequel?  More explosions and flash!  NO!!!  The original was awesome because it FELT real even if we knew it wasn't.  Things were dark and gritty.  The fights were visceral not full of "Cool" special effects.  I don't care if the Jaeger can transform, or shoot some huge multi-laser death cannon.  I want raw fights that make me feel the beatings...that's what hooked me in the original....This trailer does not inspire confidence.

text: This movie doesn't look like Pacific Rim visually. The 1st film was littered with glowing neon lights (and blood) that popped out. I felt like the 1st Pacific Rim was made to be watched in 3D. This film however is missing Guillermo's aesthetic flair. He makes all his movies in a particular way. Hellboy-Creature design. Pans Labyrinth-Whimsical Gothic set. Pacific Rim-Neon And Scale/Size shots   . Guillermo made the Jaegers look very large by scaling them, with a lot of panned shots. Having the cam pulled back doesn't make them look big. Also the Jaegers and Kaiju all look unique, the Jaegers in this film look like they were focus tested by 9 year old boys of what would look cool, but that's just what I think. Can't cast judgment on a films success on a trailer.

text: Cant wait. Good trailer, and I like the change in the tone. The dark tone from the first film wouldnt fit. In the first film, hope was nearly lost, and there were a few Jaegers left. Now, people have hope again, and there are far better Jaegers, and btw, it makes perfect sense that they'd have better mobility, or work with one pilot, after a few years.  John Boega's character being Idris Elba's character's son(it seems like it), is just absolutely perfect.  The music, its a freakin' Tupac song, of course it fits. Its not some shitty pop song, its a song from Tupac.  Also, it looked like the Kaijus have Kaiju/Jaeger hybrids. It makes sense, they're intelligent, and they would adapt to the point of having Kaiju/Jaeger hybrids.   But I hope this doesnt mean Becket and Mako from the first film are killed off, and the Kaijus have Gipsy Danger. When I think about it, that would be perfect, the Kaijus would basically be flipping off the humans by using the very thing that was supoosed to end them. I guess the Kaijus could still have Gipsy Danger, but Becket and Mako should still be around as the higher ups of these new pilots.

text: One thing people don't think about is, in an effects-heavy film like this they may still be working on it hours before its due for distribution. The biggest scenes will be worked on first, especially if they aren't waiting for live plates. So the big battles/scenes we see here are just snippets of what they have done, and this is heavily edited to drum up excitement. This is a first real trailer, that's what its FOR. There are usually 2/3 distinct trailers for a big release like this so we'll get more bits and pieces of the story as we get closer to the release.

EVERYTHING looks so unrealistic, vibrant, and kiddish. I miss the realism and those dark apocalyptic vibes that Pacific Rim 1 delivered. Now we're basically getting power rangers 2 or Transformers 6. The only thing I liked about the trailer is that it showed some corruption or one of the Jaegers betraying the government or something. I thought that was a pretty cool idea to include in the movie. But other than that, this trailer was a major disappointment. All I'm hoping for is that the movie still excels my expectations and this trailer isn't a big hint that the movie is going to suck.

text: Oh hey look, the appeal and aesthetics of the first one are completely gone. Just call this "Not Bay's Transformers: But it sure looks like it". You gave me my favorite movie and then you crapped something out and called it a sequel. Should have brought Guillermo back on for this. You somehow managed to make the cgi look worse than what the first movie presented. The jeagers are flying around seemingly weightless. You took a very cool practice effect set piece, the jeager's cockpit and replaced it with this awful cgi green screen. The music, PR's score guided you perfectly through the film, now you threw in something you'd find in a generic action movie to fit in with your transformers fight scenes. This isn't even worth a pirating. I'll continue thinking the sequel never got the green light and ignore this abomination when it comes out.
author: Ivan Grado

text: This looks like another Hollywood blockbuster/bust that's being revamped for the Asian market.¬† Kaijus and giant robots are always popular in that market.¬† At 0.49. that's Chinese actress Jing Tian (from Kong Skull Island and The Great Wall) with a few other Asians behind her walking forward in classic hero poses, and at 0.53, that giant robot is giving a classic Chinese martial arts salute to an opponent.¬† Basically we're getting Kung Fu moves from 300 feet tall robots.¬† I expect this to bomb here in the US. and do great over in China :P

text: Looks okay, though a definite departure from the gritty, dark scape of the original, which I think was a lot of the charm. The ultra-smooth movements of the jaegers are very Transformers-esque and lame. del Torro was careful to avoid that and it made the fight scenes much more interesting and visceral. Also, the suit and cockpit designs are quite boring looking. I liked the heavier machinery of the OG Gipsy Danger; now it just looks very CGIed and bland. I do adore John Boyega, but they'll have to  have some amazing writing to top "canceling the apocalypse." Also, I'm dreading how they're going to write out Raleigh--hopefully it'll just be quick and easy. I'll still fork over the cheddar to see it in theaters, but I'm going to be missing del Torro's influence greatly.

text: Got to be honest. This trailer is not what I hoped it would be. The first minute of the trailer starts out really nice; shows some of the first war, shows the new Yeager's in action a bit, and tells us about what the world is like after the war by turning the Jaegers against one anther. Kinda like what humanity would actually do in this situation and I think is a solid idea for the plot. However the rest of the trailer kinda crumbles. We see more of Jaegers vs Jaegers and who can't complain about that but then there are just these random cuts of Kaiju scenes. At first I thought these were more flashbacks but we can later see these are new Kaiju attacks. The return of the Kaiju should be a big deal like a second coming of the apocalypse and yet there just kinda there. This makes feel like there no big deal anymore. The Kaiju were the main enemy of the first film so much so that they almost won the war but having them just apear in the sequel takes all the weight they had away. And I know that this is just a trailer and that they kaiju will probably have not only a bigger presence but a better reveal in the full film but mabye keep that reveal secret mabye not show us Kaiju till the second or third trailer if at all make them feel more like villains and less like a monster of the week. I don't care if they have some special powers or whatever there appearance should shock and terrify audiences. I hope the film is far better then this trailer because I'm a big fan of  the original pacific rim and it deserves a sequel that matches or even surpasses it but all and all this trailer does not give off that feel to me, it makes me think this film will not be as good as the original and I hope I'm wrong. It is the first trailer and the visuals and acting look great so I'm still holding out hope. But the soundtrack sucks I'm sorry but these songs have been terrible in my opinion. Still hyped for Pacific rim Uprising and I hope it delivers.

text: What I loved in the first movie was the attention to detail. The Jaegers and Kaiju had a real weight to them, it really sold the idea that the movie respected physics even just a little bit compared to every other blockbuster, the attention to detail on how even water behaved while the Jaegers moved. It sold the staggering sense of scale of these things and the immersion you felt watching it was something else. They seem to have forsaken all of that in favour of your typical action blockbuster brand of excess everything. Excess fighting, excess robots, excess monsters, just make everything bigger and put more of everything, that's what makes money not attention to detail.

The trailer for the 2nd movie feels like were moving into pure fantasy.

text: Why pacific rim 1 will be better than 2 judging solely on the trailers:  -Sence of scale and weight. In 1 you can sence the weight of every punch, every move, every step. You truly feel there is a steel titan walking around carrying the best humanity can offer and it means fking business, same as a kaiju where you can feel the threat of a megamonster, thousand tons of flesh unstoppable and rampant. Where is any of that in 2? Playdoll mechs wich seem to bemoving as fast as humans, seem smaller (probably are) and so seem the kaijus. Any combat scenario created under these premuses does not feel like a clash between gargantuans, but more like a clash between a human and bear, with the difference human bear sword type weapons.  -The mechs themselves. In pacific rim 1 you could tell the individuality of the mechs, they had "character" same as their drivers, who can forget the russians? One of my two complains in PR1 was that we didnt get to see much foghting from Russian and Chinese Jaeger, but we still got something and even that little was awesome. Do you remember any of the jaegers you saw in  PR2 trailer besides the gypsy danger evolution? I dont, while i was fighting with my eyes  in the first trailer to absorb ALL extra detail in the jaegers and kaijus, in the 2nd movie trailer i felt like i didnt care, i can see them clearly and yet the item of focus is their sword not their character.  These reasons alone are 60%-70% of the movie, there are more which i wont wet into atm.

text: I am a big fan of Pacific Rim ... I would venture to say one of the biggest in the world (Not trying to be arrogant). But I can not accept what they did with the movie, this is not the Pacific Rim I know, that is: Jaegers where the neural connection was accurate and should be perfect Where there was difficulty locomotion; where most movements were limited; Where the transport should be done with Logistic aid; where each fight should be careful, since each Fight with each Kaiju was Risky, independent of the Kaiju Class or Level, where there was no Fight between Jaegers, since all Jaegers in operation served the Same Purpose, in fact that being the Purpose of the Program Jaeger (The Union of All Nations of the World against the Enemy in Common), where each Jaeger had its characteristic and was not generic, this includes Advantages, Limitations and Personality, the Soundtrack that made sense and made the film even better and each Pilot had a degree of experience, so these drivers could not be teenagers ... THIS FILM WILL NEVER BE PACIFIC RIM, JUST MORE A GENERIC MOVIE WITH ADOLESCENTS, GENERIC JAEGERS, GENERIC KAIJUS, GENERIC CHARACTERS AND GENERIC  PLOT ... This work does not has no relation with the Del Toro Work

text: Without Guillermo del Toro at the head of this movie i think it's safe to say that the fans of the first one will be desapointed.  That is not to say that this movie will be garbage, we'll just have to see, but i don't think it has been made with the same dedication that the first one. Pacific Rim one was a movie wich just felt like a big love letter to all of the old school monster movies. This new movie looks like it missed that. It's too bright, it's too hopefull, too... doll. I see a lot of people referencing the transformers and the power rangers, and i think they're right. I cared for the futur and the well being of the caracters of the first one because even if i the plot was kind of stupid it was well made and i wanted to believe it. There is no stakes at hand in this one so there is no fear for the caracters . And teenagers... seriously what the hell... i know there is monsters and robots but that don't mean you should aim at kids!  I guess i should wait and see, maybe it's just the trailer that give this feeling, the movie could be different. But unfortunatly i don't think so. Well anyway, fingers crossed!

text: Now let me get something straight, I'm not saying this movie will be bad(I can't know that yet) but this trailer is missing something the first movie's trailer had(comparing trailers, not movie to trailer). The first one had this dark, brutal feel to it. The jagers were slower and they felt powerful watching them. As for the kaiju the fact that what we saw of them was in darker conditions we felt tension and they were intimidating. Along with this Gypsey dangers design had a very metallic grey look about it. In this trailer the Kaiju look pretty good, but seem less, idk, threatening, and the jagers remind me more of the new power rangers movie looks, from weapons, to how they move. Of course the power rangers movie isn't that bad, i enjoyed it because everything they did fit for power rangers, but for pacific rim it should more brutal. Remember how churno alpha always seems like a tank no matter what it was doing, even when we meet the pilots of alpha it's size and tank like look made it intimidating, that's what pacific rim is in my mind.

text: As usual (and you'd think they would understand that we see this too much)... ¬†a sequel of an action film that has more of everything, obviously affected by gaming. (sigh)¬† Please, borrow from games as they borrow from movies, but do it tastefully and realistically. Pacific Rim's world is over the top, but Del Toro could make, with some missteps of course like anybody... ¬†an over-the-top world that you accept because the pacing and detail sneaks through, like with life. There has to be woven elements of what we see everyday such as occasional tics, flaws, and dull things that are right next to the amazing things, to help us believe something crazy is happening the next minute.

text: The worst thing about this godawful trailer is the visuals. The first Pacific Rim movie was very silly and full of wooden acting, but it looked downright beautiful. Guillermo Del Toro, a brilliant visual stylist and great director, made Pacific Rim as a silly homage to the classic monster movies he watched as a child. It was never meant to be a big, epic film, it was just meant to be fun. The world of Pacific Rim was incredibly rendered, with expressive color grading and great special effects. The CGI was incredible, and masterfully blended into real world scenery in really interesting locales like Tokyo. This movie is just any big dumb blockbuster, with CGI that already looks dated and uninteresting locations for fights. So the CGI looks like crap, and the coloration of the images is very uninteresting. They also got a director whose literally only known for the Spartacus TV show to direct it, following up GUILLERMO DEL TORO, so that gives you an idea of the kind of quality they were seeking for this product. Seriously, this looks awful, and the worst thing is that it will probably do well.

I don't like the way pilots now do full-on kung-fu in the cockpits, apparently unconstrained by harnesses. And I'm wondering why Jaegers are clearly fighting each other as much as they're fighting Kaiju. Phenomenal action scenes are all very good, but the original Pacific Rim was such a success because it also had a really good story and script. Still, I have faith.

text: are those pilots in the Conn-Pod without drive suits???? i'm so disappointed. even though the first pacific rim film was extraordinarily cheesy, it was one of my favourites because they put so much emphasis on the importance of drift compatibility, which greatly contributed to the emotional aspect of the film. Not only that, but it looks like they've completed stripped the human aspect behind each Jaeger, no pilot to pilot protocol sequence, no neural handshakes, and they've incorporated AI's which really don't fit the steam punk theme of the actual Pacific Rim universe. There's absolutely no mention or footage of the PPDC and LOCCENT human officers that made the entire program a well oiled machine either. Uprising looks like it can't even live up to a cheap transformers knock off.

text: this already looks way better than the first one. i was really hoping for jaeger vs jaeger and it seems we are getting just that, with the standard kaiju action, which is really excitiing. it looks like they ar taking everything in the most interesting direction possible, including actual alien soldiers that humans have to shoot at in fire fights, which is REALLY interesting and A TON more practical than just using kaiju to take over a planet. also seen are smaller jaegers, some appearing home made, or made with scrap parts, but it all looks oh so very interesting, i cant believe how good this looks, and how hyped i am for this. im really hoping this will revive the giant monster scene in hollywood these days. with kong and godzilla making a return, kaiju films have had more spotlight in america recently than perhaps ever before, however, they arent comic book movie scale of success and or popularity, but im hoping that soon changes. i doubt it, but kaiju films deserve a place amoung modern western culture, in my opinion.

text: Why is it that people accept anything from superhero movies (specially Marvel's) even if its ridiculous and far-fetched but everyone wants giant robot and kaiju films to be realistic? This attitude is utterly stupid, if the film was to be realistic then it shouldn't exist in the first place because its whole premise is based on ludicrous and impossible feats: building 100 meter tall robots to fight giant monsters genetically engineered by an alien species. A director's creativity shouldn't be limited because of realism. If you want realism then don't watch the movie because there's no realism whatsoever in having genetically engineered giant monsters invade earth under orders of an interdimensional alien species and humans reacting by fighting back with 100 meter tall humanoid robots equiped with plasma guns.   I'm glad they're making the Jaegers move even faster because it means the studio is giving zero f*cks about those complaints that giant robot (mecha) and monster (kaiju) films have to be "realistic" in order to be produced. You see, this is what happened to Godzilla, they wanted to make it so realistic that it ended up being just an oversized animal fighting other animals when the original japanese Godzilla is more of an intelligent and sentient being that defends Earth from several threats that are either alien or man-made.

text: Mixed reactions. I am a Pacific Rim fanboy, I loved the original movie, and have been impatiently waiting for the sequel.   The things that are wrong with it... cast is way too young... think back to the first film... the young people were inexperienced, lost their cool, and didn't quite have it together ... the older people naturally guided them through ... what are they going to do in this one? Call a suicide hotline? anyway...   Lets talk about the jaegers... in the first one, their weapons were more technologically realizable... seems like every movie today has glowing swords and electric whips.... what was wrong with missiles? normal knives that Striker Eureka had? Spinning shuriken things that Crimson Typhoon had? EMP bursts? Plasma bursts? Cherno Alpha had a giant tazer we never got to see!! And what about that solenoid powered punching arm?? All realizable... but in this one... what is with that overexaggerated drill bit??? What are they doing, looking for oil in the kaiju??? CMON MAN!!!   The speed doesn't bother me at all. If you remember, striker eureka could run in water... it was normal evolution. What is important is that they maintain the umph in theaters, because fast or slow its still a heavy machine moving around. When Gypsy Danger was walking around in the city looking for the acid spitty preggo kaiju, the glass would vibrate because of the jaegers steps... THAT is umph...   We'll see how it is in theaters. I already knew Guillermo wasn't directing, which sucks, but I hope he kept his eye on what was being done to this movie.

text: For everyone complaining about how the jaegers don't look very big or that they don't carry tons of weight when they move I have to ask: do evangelions or gundams look like they weigh tons? No. Because after a while the slow moving motions would get boring. Sure, in the first pacific rim the weight of the jaegers added to the suspense, but it also kinda dragged the fight scenes down imo. A faster bot means it can react faster and have a better chance of winning. Plus the tech capabilities in this film are likely far advanced than that of #1, so they likely have the ability to move faster without being weighed down by itself. Just enjoy the frickin spectacle, this scenario isn't at all realistic anyways

text: Not to be that guy, but I'm going to complain about the music used for the trailer. I tried watching the trailer without the music and I noticed that my interpretation of what I was seeing changed drastically.  With the music, the movie is essentially selling itself as transformers or power-rangers (along with the color palette choice during the day-shots, but I think enough people have harped on the odd choice of day colors. When the music isn't big, orchestral, and powerful, the trailer is selling the movie short of its big and giant premise.   Continuing, the line-up shot at the end has the camera moving very quickly from one jaeger to another, which makes the jaeger's feel like they are tiny instead of being huge. Subtle stuff like this changes the tone of the movie very significantly.  I hope it's good, but there are a lot of things that are making me nervous (visual design choices are the main thing that are bothering me at this point).

text: Not bad I guess. It lacks the dark tone from the previous movie. The jaegar on jaegar action looks pretty good, but I can't help but feel this going to be one of those typical sequels that everyone forgets about. I would have preferred a prequel. Would've been wicked to see the mk.1's in action and it would have given them a better idea of how to move the franchise forward towards a story rich ending. The plot is off. It chops straight to where humanity is ready to duke it out with next gen jaegars. They hinted at the jaegar/kaiju hybrid in the first film and it would have been a better build up story to go through the process where the jaegar program is reinvented and refined in the time where the portal is restored or shortly after it is restored. It would have been a decent enough ending if we did not get a third movie and it could have set up an epic finale where it would have made sense to introduce an op regen kaiju. This movie feels like it's trying to simulate transformers in it has to one up itself with every release with something jaw droppingly crazy. 5/10. meh

text: I really enjoyed the first film, and this one looks like it would be fun to watch, and have tons of cool scenes, but definitely not as good as the first. I mainly liked the first film because it had an awesome idea, but was still grounded in reality because it had an industrial and gritty feel to it. This one looks more like a brightly coloured power rangers or new transformers kind of thing, with the ridiculous weapons and faster movements of the Jaggers. They are making a common mistake, thinking that if people like this one thing, making it bigger/more of it, it will be even better. Wrong. These Robots are supposed to be big, hulking machines, with disadvantages and like something humans might be able to actually make. All in all,   I think the Pacific rim classic will always be a great stand alone movie, they don't need this.  (Some of the stuff like the missile was cool though)

text: Aright first of all, I'm not gonna lie the fight scenes look awesome and I'll be cheering at every one of them. But one of the biggest loses I think this movie has, is that it doesnt have the one thing that makes the scene from the first one  work so well. *Weight.*  The Jagers from the first movie seem to move so slow, like they are *actual giant robots* that has to cover some *actual distance* to deliver even a single punch. Even though they move so slowly, it's all worth it when the punch actually came in contact with the Kaiju because when that punch hits you can just *feel* how heavy it was, how damaging that single blow was to the Kaiju.  These new Jagers seem to move so fast and yeah their weapons look cool and all, but it's a shame that the impact is gone.  The first movie was brilliant, it's gritty and realistic, but it toes the edge of sci-fi too. It gives off the feel of a world capable of having robotic limbs and flying cars but also drug deals in an alley and murder in an abandoned parking lot.  I don't know what to expect from this movie, but I hope we can still see the alley ways in this sci-fi world.  *EDIT:* For the record let me say this for the people that commented this over and over again. It is not that I dont understand *why* the Jagers are so much more light in this sequel, what I'm saying is that *the weight that we see in the first movie REALLY sold it to not just me, but a way more wider audiance and it is a shame that we cant see that again in this movie*

text: In my opinion, this is probably going to be terrible.  The first movie was beautifully executed and dynamic with surprising amount of sentience with the human settings in a monster/robot fighting movie.  The sequel seems to be the complete opposite from what I'm seeing in the trailer.  The first and the worst mistake was kicking out Guillermo del Toro from the project for directing; in his visuals, he aims for good perspective that won't make the characters too close, close realistic physics of weight and height of the robots/monsters (slow movement indicated from the first movie) while executing movements. Not only that, but the signature colors of shades of blues with streaks of warm colors.  This version, it's just not believable in the execution, there's no limited palette/gamut technique, and the camera angles are already obnoxious in the trailers.  Aka, typical Hollywood maneuvers.  Thus, I'm going to watch this when it comes out on Netflix; not worth the tickets for the theater. (This is my critique, take it as you will)

text: I DON'T LIKE IT!! A new generation?? Where is the old one? We barely had a chance to know them.The lack of Charlie Hunnam already offends me deeply, and it seems Rinko Kikuchi's also became a background dancer, because she progressively left out from the trailer. No Max Martini, Ron Pearlman, etc, only the two sidekick docs remained, I like them, but....BUT!!! B(  Honestly, I saw PR at last ten times since came out. Not a diehard fan, the story is not even THAT good, sometimes rather stupid, but there is a spark, a likeable team of actors I can rooting for(great chemistry btwn leading characters), amazing CGI scenes, good dynamism, great music.... This, on the other hand, from the trailer it feels like a kid-friendly teenage TV-show;  looks like Transformers, Power Rangers and Godzilla have an ugly foster child Lost the intention to watch it in cinema, maybe when it came out on DVD...but until that, I'll probably forgot it's even egzist. text: Nothing feels that big, that scary (including the robots), that "realistic". Doesn't feel like the earth will rumble under their feet. Feels like the robots are children's toys. I am more than certain that the CGI is going a bit towards anime rather than making it look like it just REALLY popped out of this world in real life. They might as well call it avengers, because these robots feel more human sized than actual big robot sized. I am going to watch it, because I don't want to believe that they ruined the original feeling, but it does look like it. This might be the last Pacific Rim we'll ever see... If not, there might be maximum a third Power Range... I mean Pacific Rim before it dies out forever, but I am not sure...

text: Uprising is just a Bootleg Transformer. The Robots are quick and strong, but it doesn't look like it. The Pacific Rim's Robots are slow, heavy and the sound of the metal scraping each other as they move and the mechanical noises they make is simply astounding, they look like actual gigantic robots landing heavy hits/punches. It's extremely fun and entertaining to watch. The Movie's Sound Designs are extremely satisfying and it sounds just as you expect it to sound. Gipsy Danger is straight up amazing. Meanwhile, the Uprising's Robots are much faster, pretty heavy and sounds far more advanced than they should. Big Things shouldn't move fast. It's a pretty good movie, the sound effects, soundtracks and overall being the sequel to Pacific Rims. It's not painful to watch, it's quite entertaining but when you see it closer then it's just crap. The Movie's Sound Designs are not too bad, quite good but sometime it just doesn't sound right. Gipsy Avenger is just.. No.

text: I don't know why this film has a lot of hate because I'm one of the few people who likes it. I can understand that they didn't get all the old actors from the first film to reprise their roles like Raleigh but that's probably because the actor would want lots of money to come back. Like in the MCU the actors who played Rhodey and Bruce Banner in their debut were later replaced by different actors because the old actors wanted more money and yet nobody complains about them now. The other issue people have is the CGI saying it looks bad but the first movie was always in shown in the dark but if it was shown more during the day you wouldn't complain. The next issue people have is how the jaegers don't have height to them and how you can't feel their hits like in the first film but you also have to remember that these are Mark 5 to 7 Jaegers and they're more advanced than the Mark 1 to 4 jaegers. They're not going to rebuild old jaegers to fight against newer kaiju that might have the advantage in battle. So they made newer models to keep up. And there's the issue that they look the same. I beg to differ, they look completely different to me. And people complain that kids are the ones piloting the jaegers. Are you serious I see nothing wrong with that, we've seen it done in hundreds of anime so why are you complaining now. The next issue is Stacker's son who was never mentioned in the first film. Maybe he was never mentioned was because his father probably disowned him after trying to pilot a jaeger by himself and failed. Next issue was killing off Mako and yes I will agree with that but remember what I said about actors needing money but it did serve as a good motivation for Jake to become a pilot and save the world. The next biggest issue was the kaiju were always heading for Mt. Fuji. Remember what Newton said in the first film the Precursors sent the Kaiju to attack cities to soften them up and then send the bigger threats. They were most likely trying to eliminate any threats that would interfere with their plans to take over the earth. The Kaiju's position of where they were at the time just happen to be towards the direction of Mt. Fuji.

A lot of bashers didnt seem to think of that. Still, part one was the best. The horror, the suspense and all.   so in short, the hate and the obnoxious comments about this movie is EXAGGERATED. its totally rewatchable and a good sequel. Maybe the only thing i didnt like was killing the female lead from the first movie
